1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:18,000
I'm Emily Crosby and this is December 1st, 2015 and I'm here with Mr. Vernon-Damer Jr.

3
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:25,000
at the University of Southern Mississippi at the program on oral history and cultural heritage.

4
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:35,000
And with me is John Bishop and Gouha Shankar and we're doing this interview as part of the Civil Rights History Project,

5
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:42,000
co-sponsored by the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

6
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:46,000
So thank you so much for joining us and doing the interview.

7
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:47,000
You are?

8
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:54,000
Mr. Damer, could you tell us when and where you were born and about your family history?

9
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:18,000
Yes, I was born in the Kelly's Selmet community about five miles north of Hadesburg where we are today in August 27th, 1929.

10
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:20,000
Tell me about your family.

11
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:26,000
Okay.

12
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:32,000
My dad, Vernon-F-Damer Sr.

13
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:44,000
was one of 12 children born to George, Damer, and Ellie Kelly, Damer.

14
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:55,000
He was the youngest of 12 kids, six boys and six girls.

15
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:07,000
One of the boys died in the infant so that left a family of five boys and six girls.

16
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:21,000
Being the way segregation was back in that day discrimination in the oppressive situation for blacks in Mississippi

17
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:34,000
and where the black race had very little defense from law enforcement.

18
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:54,000
My grandfather made a conscious effort to make sure that his six-female daughters had the opportunity to leave the state of Mississippi at a very young age.

19
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:05,000
It was for their own protection because it was pretty obvious at that time that the white male retreated to black male,

20
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:12,000
as if he wanted to, my grandfather, he saw this being raised born and raised in Mississippi.

21
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:22,000
And likewise, the male sons all except my father who was the youngest boy.

22
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:25,000
They left the state also and went north.

23
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:26,000
So your father is the only one?

24
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:30,000
My father was the only one to remain here.

25
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:37,000
And since he was a baby boy, I would imagine he was the closest to the parents, you know, being the baby.

26
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:41,000
And he worked on a farm.

27
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:47,000
And he made a decision to remain and not leave the state.

28
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:59,000
The old males went ahead and assimilated into the society in Chicago in those places where they were identified as Caucasians, which is fine.

29
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:01,000
Because you were going looking for a better life.

30
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:04,000
I don't fault them at all about that.

31
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:07,000
It's with situation where if you don't ask, you don't tell.

32
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:15,000
So he was not asked because of all of them, because all of them are very, very late, completed and just run off, but they look like whites.

33
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:20,000
So the simulation was not that difficult.

34
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:27,000
And they were very fortunate in landing good employment.

35
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:34,000
The females, all of them went north and they married African American men, a black man.

36
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:36,000
It's interesting that the...

37
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:38,000
Yes, it was.

38
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:47,000
Do you have a speculation about why the women did one thing and the men did something different?

39
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:49,000
No, I don't.

40
00:04:49,000 --> 00:05:03,000
Probably realizing, you know, in being raised in the South, it was probably easier to find suitable black man to marry.

41
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:12,000
Not being close to affiliated with the white males in Mississippi, they feel comfortable, you know, being in the black environment.

42
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:15,000
I would just imagine that was a reason why.

43
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:25,000
And the same applied to me when I went into military in 1951, being raised in all black community.

44
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:31,000
I never really hadn't noticed how to pass when you were raised in being African American.

45
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:38,000
I was married to a dark skin African American woman and I was very comfortable.

46
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:43,000
Did the men who were assimilated, did they stay in touch with the family?

47
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:46,000
Yes, yes they did.

48
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:51,000
They would come and visit an old occasion.

49
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:57,000
One or maybe two of them would bring their wives, white with them.

50
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:09,000
And that was not hard to do at that time because due to the complexion of the family and there were other mixed races in the community.

51
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:14,000
Out of the way to work, they needed to have food increasing.

52
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:21,000
To be fair, being able to brok in the community area, they had to tire for a lot of the problems that came the light skinened Americans.

53
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:27,000
So inastaia, just being able to keep that population low, you know, because overall.

54
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:31,300
And that came out of slavery, you know, as a result of the mixing of the races by the

55
00:06:31,300 --> 00:06:35,740
slave master and his family, you know.

56
00:06:35,740 --> 00:06:40,540
So, so that when they come here, it's almost like the lights are passing.

57
00:06:40,540 --> 00:06:42,140
Yeah.

58
00:06:42,140 --> 00:06:45,380
And they they felt comfortable, you know, and moving around.

59
00:06:45,380 --> 00:06:49,620
I never saw any anxiety, but being a little boy, you know, I didn't put it in any way.

60
00:06:49,620 --> 00:06:50,620
You didn't eat it anyway.

61
00:06:50,620 --> 00:06:52,220
Yeah, they were just people visiting.

62
00:06:52,220 --> 00:06:53,220
Right.

63
00:06:53,220 --> 00:06:59,340
So, my senses are I've been told by some people that Kelly Settlement and some of the other

64
00:06:59,340 --> 00:07:06,900
areas, you know, as you were saying, a lot of mixed race people that there was a sense

65
00:07:06,900 --> 00:07:12,260
at least among some people of being kind of in between, that they didn't really identify.

66
00:07:12,260 --> 00:07:15,780
You've been saying you identify with the black community, but I've heard some people say

67
00:07:15,780 --> 00:07:20,300
that they didn't identify one or another, that they sort of had independence.

68
00:07:20,300 --> 00:07:21,300
There we are.

69
00:07:21,300 --> 00:07:23,820
Are you aware of that?

70
00:07:23,820 --> 00:07:25,340
It could have happened.

71
00:07:25,340 --> 00:07:27,100
Pardon me.

72
00:07:27,100 --> 00:07:29,900
It could have happened.

73
00:07:29,900 --> 00:07:38,700
But coming out of the family where I never saw any racial separation of division, my

74
00:07:38,700 --> 00:07:42,580
grandparents and my parents always treated everybody the same.

75
00:07:42,580 --> 00:07:44,100
My school was all black.

76
00:07:44,100 --> 00:07:46,260
My church was all black.

77
00:07:46,260 --> 00:07:53,700
And consequently, I didn't have any notions about going over to the other race or being

78
00:07:53,700 --> 00:07:54,860
maybe out of place.

79
00:07:54,860 --> 00:07:59,380
I felt very comfortable being black and like watch today.

80
00:07:59,380 --> 00:08:01,780
And went through the military feeling that way.

81
00:08:01,780 --> 00:08:05,220
Black and from Mississippi, oh no, you're not all you say, I am.

82
00:08:05,220 --> 00:08:09,740
In other words, I'm not making an assumption to where it was.

83
00:08:09,740 --> 00:08:11,980
You're not going to change who I am.

84
00:08:11,980 --> 00:08:13,820
Oh, no, no, no.

85
00:08:13,820 --> 00:08:16,300
And I saw that coming out of my family.

86
00:08:16,300 --> 00:08:21,460
My grandfather, George Damon, which you probably want to heard of this, he was white.

87
00:08:21,460 --> 00:08:23,780
You know, he was third-bring white.

88
00:08:23,780 --> 00:08:26,380
His mother was white.

89
00:08:26,380 --> 00:08:33,860
And his dad was German, Peter Damon, from Domstadt, Germany.

90
00:08:33,860 --> 00:08:36,060
I spent my time in the military.

91
00:08:36,060 --> 00:08:38,420
And he was white.

92
00:08:39,140 --> 00:08:47,140
My grandfather's mother was born out of Wittlock, Laura Barnes.

93
00:08:47,140 --> 00:08:52,380
And she was placed with a Milato woman to raise.

94
00:08:52,380 --> 00:08:58,100
And while being there with the Milato lady who was a Barnes, because you know, they carried

95
00:08:58,100 --> 00:09:00,140
a slave name on the hall.

96
00:09:00,140 --> 00:09:06,940
This Milato lady was running a boarding house up in Covington County, not about 25 miles

97
00:09:06,940 --> 00:09:09,340
from here.

98
00:09:09,340 --> 00:09:17,140
And that's where my grandfather's mother lived and worked.

99
00:09:17,140 --> 00:09:20,180
And then he was in the Domstadt family.

100
00:09:20,180 --> 00:09:21,660
So he was raised in that?

101
00:09:21,660 --> 00:09:27,420
Sure, the Domstadt family migrated from Germany because of economic conditions over there.

102
00:09:27,420 --> 00:09:30,180
It was like five of those brothers.

103
00:09:30,180 --> 00:09:34,980
And one of the older brothers settled there in the area and he became a queen with my grandfather's

104
00:09:34,980 --> 00:09:36,620
mother.

105
00:09:36,620 --> 00:09:39,140
And they had a child.

106
00:09:39,140 --> 00:09:45,620
And then later on, my grandfather, George Damon, grew up in that environment.

107
00:09:45,620 --> 00:09:54,860
And his mother, Laura, she hired this black guy, Charlie Kraft, to work for her in a business.

108
00:09:54,860 --> 00:10:01,460
And I think she ran a boarding house with the woodcutters and all also, eventually.

109
00:10:01,460 --> 00:10:04,180
And then she married an ex-slave, Charlie Kraft.

110
00:10:04,180 --> 00:10:07,220
They went on to have nine mixed race kids.

111
00:10:07,220 --> 00:10:10,380
My grandfather, George Damon, he was the oldest son.

112
00:10:10,380 --> 00:10:11,380
Okay.

113
00:10:11,380 --> 00:10:14,100
Yeah, he was the oldest son in that mixed race family.

114
00:10:14,100 --> 00:10:21,080
Now when they got married, even though Laura, my grandfather's mother was assumed to be

115
00:10:21,080 --> 00:10:27,300
Milato because she had been raised up in a Milato family.

116
00:10:27,300 --> 00:10:29,300
That was okay as long as she was unmarried.

117
00:10:29,300 --> 00:10:32,100
But when she married Charlie Kraft, I thought having kids.

118
00:10:32,100 --> 00:10:35,460
And then the old, old white Natty, I was like, hey, we don't go.

119
00:10:35,460 --> 00:10:39,340
Right, it's okay for them to be together, but not for them to be married.

120
00:10:39,340 --> 00:10:40,940
Right, and to have kids.

121
00:10:40,940 --> 00:10:42,700
And they started that, okay.

122
00:10:42,700 --> 00:10:43,700
Kids at the end.

123
00:10:43,700 --> 00:10:46,620
And then they had to leave from there and move down in the commuter guerrilla.

124
00:10:46,620 --> 00:10:49,700
And why was it okay for them to be in Kelly's settlement?

125
00:10:49,700 --> 00:10:53,900
Because there were a lot of Milato's, that Kelly family, which my grandmother came out of.

126
00:10:53,900 --> 00:10:54,900
Okay.

127
00:10:54,900 --> 00:10:57,380
My dad's mother, Helen Kelly Damer.

128
00:10:57,380 --> 00:11:02,100
And by the way, her mother was also white.

129
00:11:02,100 --> 00:11:11,620
She was born out of Redlock and she was put with a black family, McCone family, to be

130
00:11:11,620 --> 00:11:13,420
raised.

131
00:11:13,420 --> 00:11:20,780
And that's how she met it with my grandmother, Helen Kelly's, their dad warned Kelly, okay.

132
00:11:20,780 --> 00:11:24,220
Because there were two, there were two on Milato and white.

133
00:11:24,620 --> 00:11:28,420
So that's where you got this real light complex of the rate.

134
00:11:28,420 --> 00:11:31,180
But there were other families out in our community.

135
00:11:31,180 --> 00:11:35,020
Blackwise, Wilson family, Eaton family.

136
00:11:35,020 --> 00:11:39,060
At one time, our family was identified, you know, it's kind of a sling.

137
00:11:39,060 --> 00:11:41,380
That's where all the white Negroes live.

138
00:11:41,380 --> 00:11:48,380
We talked to Mrs. Smith earlier today and she said she was called that white Negro.

139
00:11:48,380 --> 00:11:50,300
Mrs. Wynn, which one?

140
00:11:50,300 --> 00:11:51,300
Jeanette.

141
00:11:51,300 --> 00:11:52,540
Oh, Jeanette, I know it's Jeanette.

142
00:11:52,540 --> 00:11:55,140
Yeah, she said she had that same name.

143
00:11:55,140 --> 00:11:56,140
Yeah, of course.

144
00:11:56,140 --> 00:11:57,740
She was around Soso, Mississippi.

145
00:11:57,740 --> 00:11:58,740
Yeah, that's what she was.

146
00:11:58,740 --> 00:12:00,500
Yeah, she was a Musco, I know.

147
00:12:00,500 --> 00:12:01,500
Helen, yeah.

148
00:12:01,500 --> 00:12:02,500
Not a mixed race.

149
00:12:02,500 --> 00:12:08,900
It's a, you know, the part of Mississippi, I'm from, there were few individuals but not

150
00:12:08,900 --> 00:12:14,540
the families like this, that I was aware of growing up in the community.

151
00:12:14,540 --> 00:12:18,180
The Hattiesburg seems in this area.

152
00:12:18,180 --> 00:12:19,180
Is that true?

153
00:12:19,180 --> 00:12:21,580
Does Hattiesburg have more mixed race families?

154
00:12:21,580 --> 00:12:27,100
Well, I have nothing to compare it with, but we had a lot of them.

155
00:12:27,100 --> 00:12:28,100
Yeah.

156
00:12:28,100 --> 00:12:29,600
A lot of them, sure.

157
00:12:29,600 --> 00:12:35,820
Can you tell me what it was like growing up on your, well, you had a farm, your family

158
00:12:35,820 --> 00:12:36,820
farm?

159
00:12:36,820 --> 00:12:38,820
Can you tell us about that?

160
00:12:38,820 --> 00:12:39,820
Yes.

161
00:12:39,820 --> 00:12:46,060
My dad being the youngest son and naturally involved in farming, that was his first occupation.

162
00:12:46,060 --> 00:12:50,100
You know, being there within my grandfather, George, they my own several hundred acres of

163
00:12:50,100 --> 00:12:56,340
land and he was a very, very successful farmer.

164
00:12:56,340 --> 00:13:02,740
And having to raise 12 kids, you know, on his farm, you had to be good to feed him because

165
00:13:02,740 --> 00:13:05,780
there were no public service jobs out.

166
00:13:05,780 --> 00:13:12,460
And their family is really lived on mostly what they raised on the farm.

167
00:13:12,460 --> 00:13:14,460
Pardon me.

168
00:13:14,460 --> 00:13:19,340
Consequently, my dad, so this is just a normal way of life.

169
00:13:19,340 --> 00:13:27,700
And he liked it and he became a landowner after he married my mother and my mother is

170
00:13:27,700 --> 00:13:30,540
from the same community.

171
00:13:30,540 --> 00:13:36,580
And my grandfather gave him a little land and a start and then he went on to go to the

172
00:13:36,580 --> 00:13:40,700
inquiries on land, but there was a jaunting properties.

173
00:13:40,700 --> 00:13:46,540
And my dad became successful in the business.

174
00:13:46,540 --> 00:13:57,500
And early, I would say in the mid 1930s, my dad born in 1908 by that time he was like

175
00:13:57,500 --> 00:14:02,860
26, 27 years old.

176
00:14:02,860 --> 00:14:10,420
He bought a school bus because the days of segregated schools, the black kids had to have

177
00:14:10,420 --> 00:14:19,980
transportation so the white school system loosened up and allowed independent individuals

178
00:14:19,980 --> 00:14:24,540
to go buy a bus to transport black kids to and from school.

179
00:14:24,540 --> 00:14:28,580
So what that did, my dad bought the school bus and that put him earning more income to

180
00:14:28,580 --> 00:14:30,180
supplement the family.

181
00:14:30,180 --> 00:14:32,700
So if he bought it, they would pay him to drive it?

182
00:14:32,700 --> 00:14:36,820
And he leased his services in the bus to the county and they would pay him to die.

183
00:14:36,820 --> 00:14:40,020
And then in the meantime, when he got the...

184
00:14:40,020 --> 00:14:43,580
So he both simultaneously earned something and get his kids to school?

185
00:14:43,580 --> 00:14:44,580
Right.

186
00:14:44,580 --> 00:14:48,780
And not only that, by buying the bus, he had the opportunity to provide public service to

187
00:14:48,780 --> 00:14:54,100
other people in the community, organizations or whatever, because during that time, we

188
00:14:54,100 --> 00:14:58,540
would come now to the person that's very little personal transportation around.

189
00:14:58,540 --> 00:15:04,260
So he hauled people to Sunday school conventions, church conventions, basketball games, which

190
00:15:04,260 --> 00:15:07,300
supplemented his income.

191
00:15:07,300 --> 00:15:12,780
And he continued to do that until 1940.

192
00:15:12,780 --> 00:15:15,820
And I remember these days because at that time, I was born twenty-one, I was like eleven

193
00:15:15,820 --> 00:15:19,460
years old, oldest kid, or eight kids.

194
00:15:19,460 --> 00:15:22,300
You had a lot of responsibility, I imagine.

195
00:15:22,300 --> 00:15:24,860
Yes, and I grew up with responsibility.

196
00:15:24,860 --> 00:15:32,900
And all the farmers in the area, this whole area, they were using animals to fall.

197
00:15:32,900 --> 00:15:38,700
And had not yet arrived in this area, not to any extent the work was noticeable in the

198
00:15:38,700 --> 00:15:40,700
family fall.

199
00:15:40,700 --> 00:15:48,220
Consequently, in 1940, the war was starting in Europe, as you well know.

200
00:15:48,220 --> 00:15:53,500
And Camp Shelby is just south of here, about fifteen miles, and it was one of the major

201
00:15:53,500 --> 00:15:56,340
training camps.

202
00:15:56,340 --> 00:15:59,780
And it started to grow to provide what?

203
00:15:59,780 --> 00:16:03,180
And it was just a war, a war, a war, a war, a war.

204
00:16:03,180 --> 00:16:06,660
That created jobs because the camp had the growth to do this.

205
00:16:06,660 --> 00:16:10,500
That means black folks that were living on the farm had a chance to leave the farm, not

206
00:16:10,500 --> 00:16:15,420
leave the farm, go and work to supplement their farm income.

207
00:16:15,420 --> 00:16:21,460
So what Dad did then, he saw an opportunity with that extra money to go and buy him a

208
00:16:21,460 --> 00:16:22,460
new tractor.

209
00:16:22,460 --> 00:16:26,060
So he used the income from working Camp Shelby?

210
00:16:26,060 --> 00:16:34,460
No, he used the income from, he used the improvement in the economy.

211
00:16:34,460 --> 00:16:35,460
Got it.

212
00:16:35,460 --> 00:16:36,460
Okay.

213
00:16:36,460 --> 00:16:43,860
Well, you know, to bring more money into the community, you know, and he had more activity

214
00:16:43,860 --> 00:16:45,980
with what he had already gone all.

215
00:16:45,980 --> 00:16:50,860
And he was using his voice to transport people to him from Camp Shelby to work and all.

216
00:16:50,860 --> 00:16:56,060
So what he decided to take that extra money and bought him a tractor and all of the

217
00:16:56,060 --> 00:17:00,500
implements and goes along to do his run his farm in operation.

218
00:17:00,500 --> 00:17:02,780
He would have been really in the forefront of that.

219
00:17:02,780 --> 00:17:04,460
He was in the forefront.

220
00:17:04,460 --> 00:17:05,860
He was only guiding the neighborhood.

221
00:17:05,860 --> 00:17:07,380
Why don't black out the tractor for us?

222
00:17:07,380 --> 00:17:08,380
We know.

223
00:17:08,380 --> 00:17:10,300
Deppin' with black folks.

224
00:17:10,300 --> 00:17:16,100
And when he bought the tractor, well, other farmers in the area would use mues and horses.

225
00:17:16,100 --> 00:17:19,860
And by my dad having a tractor, he could cultivate more land.

226
00:17:19,860 --> 00:17:25,580
And he expanded his farm, because we used the tractor to assist all the farmers and

227
00:17:25,580 --> 00:17:29,500
work that they needed, you know, to move them forward.

228
00:17:29,500 --> 00:17:38,860
And then around 1942, when the war was really moving along in the black community had money

229
00:17:38,860 --> 00:17:42,940
coming in, my dad said, hey, now it's time to open a grocery store.

230
00:17:42,940 --> 00:17:46,540
So he opened a grocery store adjacent to the house.

231
00:17:47,100 --> 00:17:50,580
He was really a very savvy business person.

232
00:17:50,580 --> 00:17:52,340
He was a move in a shaker.

233
00:17:52,340 --> 00:17:58,140
Only had a 10th grade education, and he'd take chances that I would have bought that.

234
00:17:58,140 --> 00:18:05,420
But being raised the way he was in a progressive home, my grandfather was not opening that

235
00:18:05,420 --> 00:18:10,340
progressive, but he was a move in a shaker by him having landed and had his success in

236
00:18:10,340 --> 00:18:11,340
it.

237
00:18:11,900 --> 00:18:18,380
And my grandfather, my dad, were very close friends to them, okay, they worked in partnership.

238
00:18:18,380 --> 00:18:22,580
But by that time, my grandfather's getting up in age and the farming now is moving toward

239
00:18:22,580 --> 00:18:24,580
my dad and his family, us boys.

240
00:18:24,580 --> 00:18:25,900
So he's taking more responsibility.

241
00:18:25,900 --> 00:18:26,900
Right.

242
00:18:26,900 --> 00:18:27,900
He's taking more responsibility.

243
00:18:27,900 --> 00:18:28,900
Bill is a consequent land.

244
00:18:28,900 --> 00:18:32,500
They had built grocery store, a country grocery store.

245
00:18:32,500 --> 00:18:37,220
And in that country grocery store, then in the black neighborhood, he also attracted some

246
00:18:37,220 --> 00:18:39,260
white customers.

247
00:18:39,260 --> 00:18:44,180
And the grocery store was fully equipped with everything going in canned good.

248
00:18:44,180 --> 00:18:48,540
And very little electricity in that area at that time.

249
00:18:48,540 --> 00:18:54,100
A lot of people living in the country had ice boxes and they used black ice for special

250
00:18:54,100 --> 00:18:55,100
treats.

251
00:18:55,100 --> 00:19:00,620
So he built a little ice house right next to the grocery store.

252
00:19:00,620 --> 00:19:01,980
Where would he get the ice?

253
00:19:01,980 --> 00:19:06,660
We bought it down at the head of the wholesale that sold it to restaurants and all.

254
00:19:06,660 --> 00:19:12,700
And one of my jobs was to take that school bus and go down and hold in 300 pound blocks

255
00:19:12,700 --> 00:19:18,180
ice and deliver them on a Friday and bring them and put them in ice house and chip them

256
00:19:18,180 --> 00:19:20,500
into 15, 25 pound blocks.

257
00:19:20,500 --> 00:19:25,060
So I could say that was one of my jobs, okay.

258
00:19:25,060 --> 00:19:27,660
And being in the summertime, I didn't mind it too much.

259
00:19:27,660 --> 00:19:30,860
But the ice house was built homemade.

260
00:19:30,860 --> 00:19:35,460
And the salt is in the side, the insulation is in the bottom.

261
00:19:35,460 --> 00:19:36,460
It was quite cool.

262
00:19:36,460 --> 00:19:38,220
How did he know how to do that?

263
00:19:38,220 --> 00:19:39,220
He just smart guy.

264
00:19:39,220 --> 00:19:40,740
That's all I can say.

265
00:19:40,740 --> 00:19:44,460
Did you help build?

266
00:19:44,460 --> 00:19:48,180
No, at that time I was only about 14, 15 years old going to school.

267
00:19:48,180 --> 00:19:51,700
You know my interest was like, I'm doing what I'm being told to do.

268
00:19:51,700 --> 00:19:57,460
And I'm doing what I'm being told to do, too, without any question, okay.

269
00:19:57,460 --> 00:20:03,260
And by being out in the forefront, I was kind of comparing, you know, boys, you know,

270
00:20:03,260 --> 00:20:05,620
I'm doing this, I can drive a tractor, you can't.

271
00:20:05,620 --> 00:20:06,620
Right.

272
00:20:06,620 --> 00:20:07,620
And you got that time.

273
00:20:07,620 --> 00:20:08,620
You find them you.

274
00:20:08,620 --> 00:20:09,620
You find them you.

275
00:20:09,620 --> 00:20:12,940
So, you know, I felt real good about who I was.

276
00:20:12,940 --> 00:20:17,220
But whenever it did feel like, you know, there was never that atmosphere, you were better

277
00:20:17,220 --> 00:20:20,500
than somebody else, okay.

278
00:20:20,500 --> 00:20:25,100
That just never crept into the picture because I saw my family just maintaining like they

279
00:20:25,100 --> 00:20:26,580
always were.

280
00:20:26,580 --> 00:20:30,140
And your family talked to you all about that or was it just how they acted?

281
00:20:30,140 --> 00:20:31,140
No, no, not acted.

282
00:20:31,140 --> 00:20:32,140
Yeah.

283
00:20:32,140 --> 00:20:36,100
You know, go to black son, go to black son in school, everything you do is black.

284
00:20:36,100 --> 00:20:37,100
Right.

285
00:20:37,100 --> 00:20:38,100
Say irrigation kept us what?

286
00:20:38,100 --> 00:20:40,100
He kept us together.

287
00:20:40,100 --> 00:20:44,300
In a way, integration really affected our unity.

288
00:20:44,300 --> 00:20:47,380
You didn't have a choice before about being.

289
00:20:47,380 --> 00:20:48,940
We depending on one another.

290
00:20:48,940 --> 00:20:52,580
And having the same people couldn't escape it.

291
00:20:52,580 --> 00:20:54,100
No, you couldn't escape it.

292
00:20:54,340 --> 00:20:57,340
Now, if you step side to your bounder, you were in deep trouble.

293
00:20:57,340 --> 00:20:58,340
Yeah.

294
00:20:58,340 --> 00:20:59,340
Right.

295
00:20:59,340 --> 00:21:03,420
And what you did to you, you learned, you didn't learn, you just comfortably in an environment

296
00:21:03,420 --> 00:21:04,820
because you do nothing else.

297
00:21:04,820 --> 00:21:05,820
Yeah.

298
00:21:05,820 --> 00:21:07,940
So, you were going up, so you were working on the farm.

299
00:21:07,940 --> 00:21:08,940
I worked on the farm.

300
00:21:08,940 --> 00:21:11,620
I started all working on the farm as soon as I was making up.

301
00:21:11,620 --> 00:21:13,780
And then we made the logs and chickens.

302
00:21:13,780 --> 00:21:14,780
Went into the grocery business.

303
00:21:14,780 --> 00:21:15,780
I learned how to cut meat.

304
00:21:15,780 --> 00:21:17,780
We put it on cattle.

305
00:21:17,860 --> 00:21:19,700
Most cases.

306
00:21:19,700 --> 00:21:27,620
And then we, and then around 1945, now my dad had a grocery business going on.

307
00:21:27,620 --> 00:21:32,460
We had a school bus business and had the farm.

308
00:21:32,460 --> 00:21:36,500
And my dad is having all these boys in a row, see.

309
00:21:36,500 --> 00:21:38,140
And that's good labor at that point.

310
00:21:38,140 --> 00:21:40,140
Hey boy, get in house labor.

311
00:21:40,140 --> 00:21:41,140
Okay.

312
00:21:41,140 --> 00:21:43,140
What kind of salary were you getting?

313
00:21:43,140 --> 00:21:44,140
Hey.

314
00:21:44,140 --> 00:21:45,140
Sleeping boys?

315
00:21:45,140 --> 00:21:46,140
Sleeping boys.

316
00:21:46,140 --> 00:21:47,140
That's what Wade always looking for.

317
00:21:47,140 --> 00:21:48,140
Right.

318
00:21:48,140 --> 00:21:49,140
Right.

319
00:21:49,140 --> 00:21:52,340
Room and board and a little spending money on a weekend, which was not very much either.

320
00:21:52,340 --> 00:21:53,700
Did you get, did you have candy?

321
00:21:53,700 --> 00:21:56,260
Did you get spending, penny candy at the store?

322
00:21:56,260 --> 00:21:57,260
Oh, oh yeah.

323
00:21:57,260 --> 00:21:58,260
Yeah.

324
00:21:58,260 --> 00:22:01,260
You could do that, but you know, you had to watch it.

325
00:22:01,260 --> 00:22:02,260
Yeah.

326
00:22:02,260 --> 00:22:03,260
Yeah.

327
00:22:03,260 --> 00:22:04,260
We were very disciplined.

328
00:22:04,260 --> 00:22:05,260
Yeah.

329
00:22:05,260 --> 00:22:07,940
But you still see a little bit of a reminder that the boys could be boys.

330
00:22:07,940 --> 00:22:08,940
Yeah.

331
00:22:08,940 --> 00:22:16,820
And in 1945, when the war effort was really moving, you know, in Europe and in the Pacific

332
00:22:16,820 --> 00:22:25,340
area, there was more money coming into the Hattiesburg, more black folks being employed

333
00:22:25,340 --> 00:22:27,540
to supplement their income.

334
00:22:27,540 --> 00:22:33,300
So my dad went off and bought a saw meal, a small saw meal, because we had a lot of land,

335
00:22:33,300 --> 00:22:35,380
a lot of temporal, and all.

336
00:22:35,380 --> 00:22:37,140
And first he started cutting his own term.

337
00:22:37,140 --> 00:22:42,740
And he had a little, had two guys that he worked with, had experience.

338
00:22:42,740 --> 00:22:44,140
And then there we were.

339
00:22:44,140 --> 00:22:46,420
And so we started in what?

340
00:22:46,420 --> 00:22:51,620
We had dogs and cutting lumber and for sale in the neighborhood.

341
00:22:51,620 --> 00:22:55,500
And the other folks heard about it first saying, I know, the lumped businesses started

342
00:22:55,500 --> 00:22:57,140
in the flourish.

343
00:22:57,140 --> 00:23:02,580
And dad was selling his lumber to local farmers, or whoever to build barns and chicken houses

344
00:23:02,580 --> 00:23:04,580
and outhouses.

345
00:23:04,580 --> 00:23:08,700
So we had three areas of income going on, okay?

346
00:23:08,700 --> 00:23:16,380
When we spoke with your mother, well, Mrs. Damer, she told me that your father, you know,

347
00:23:16,380 --> 00:23:22,060
knew which trees the boards came from in the house that was burned down.

348
00:23:22,060 --> 00:23:23,300
Oh, yeah, yeah, sure.

349
00:23:23,300 --> 00:23:27,100
When was that house built?

350
00:23:27,100 --> 00:23:30,860
I was away in the military.

351
00:23:30,860 --> 00:23:37,420
And it had to be built probably in the early 60s or late 50s, I don't remember.

352
00:23:37,420 --> 00:23:41,980
So did you grow up in that same spot where the house is now?

353
00:23:41,980 --> 00:23:42,980
Oh, yes, I grew up then.

354
00:23:42,980 --> 00:23:43,980
It was a new house.

355
00:23:43,980 --> 00:23:44,980
It was a new house.

356
00:23:44,980 --> 00:23:49,340
Fire bombing had destroyed, which was a new house that they were living in to when the

357
00:23:49,340 --> 00:23:50,940
fire bombing took place.

358
00:23:50,940 --> 00:23:53,580
So they had already had one destroyed?

359
00:23:53,580 --> 00:23:54,580
Well, no.

360
00:23:54,580 --> 00:23:56,420
The house I grew up was the older regional home.

361
00:23:56,420 --> 00:23:57,580
That's what I was wondering about.

362
00:23:57,580 --> 00:24:01,620
And then they built a new home after my dad married my stepmother, Ellen.

363
00:24:01,620 --> 00:24:02,620
Okay.

364
00:24:02,620 --> 00:24:03,620
But she's been in the family.

365
00:24:03,620 --> 00:24:04,620
She's our mother.

366
00:24:04,620 --> 00:24:05,620
Yeah.

367
00:24:05,620 --> 00:24:07,420
She's been in the family of 60 or something years, okay?

368
00:24:07,420 --> 00:24:08,420
She's been your mother, 60 years?

369
00:24:08,420 --> 00:24:09,420
Oh, oh, yeah.

370
00:24:09,420 --> 00:24:13,860
And she's a real fine lady, you know, and everything worked out fine.

371
00:24:13,860 --> 00:24:19,060
My dad, Mom, they married in 1928 and they divorced about 1935.

372
00:24:19,060 --> 00:24:21,380
My dad had three boys by her.

373
00:24:21,380 --> 00:24:24,060
So we got three sets of kids.

374
00:24:24,060 --> 00:24:27,060
Three by my mother, three by another.

375
00:24:27,060 --> 00:24:31,500
The second wife, she died at 31 years old, some kind of muscular disease.

376
00:24:31,500 --> 00:24:37,180
And then he married the existing mother in 1952.

377
00:24:37,180 --> 00:24:39,580
I've been married then more year.

378
00:24:39,580 --> 00:24:40,580
My kids are the same age.

379
00:24:40,580 --> 00:24:41,580
She'll hold them in.

380
00:24:41,580 --> 00:24:44,660
Then you're youngest.

381
00:24:44,660 --> 00:24:46,860
So let me just ask you one more.

382
00:24:46,860 --> 00:24:56,140
So in 1935, so I'm trying to, so you were about six years old.

383
00:24:56,140 --> 00:25:02,740
So did you have a relationship with your mother after they divorced?

384
00:25:02,740 --> 00:25:08,740
Yeah, for about two or two and a half years because her family only lived about three miles

385
00:25:08,740 --> 00:25:10,240
from where we lived.

386
00:25:10,240 --> 00:25:13,840
They lived all in the same community.

387
00:25:13,840 --> 00:25:19,520
And my mother took the baby boy with her to live with the grandparents.

388
00:25:19,520 --> 00:25:28,440
And my dad kept the two older kids my brother and I because we, he didn't have no money

389
00:25:28,440 --> 00:25:29,920
to pay child support.

390
00:25:29,920 --> 00:25:34,720
And Jerry's he told me to Jerry's see you keep him and feed him.

391
00:25:34,720 --> 00:25:35,720
Okay.

392
00:25:36,720 --> 00:25:41,040
He didn't talk about that because my mom, my mother, my maternal mother, my dad had

393
00:25:41,040 --> 00:25:42,840
a beautiful relationship.

394
00:25:42,840 --> 00:25:48,040
And they were heard, either what I'm talking about, or they even have to divorce.

395
00:25:48,040 --> 00:25:51,000
Which I definitely appreciate when I grew up.

396
00:25:51,000 --> 00:25:52,000
That makes sense.

397
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:53,200
It's not always the case.

398
00:25:53,200 --> 00:25:59,040
So my mom took the baby and my dad then took us and he didn't dump us on our grandparents

399
00:25:59,040 --> 00:26:00,040
who lived nearby.

400
00:26:00,040 --> 00:26:01,040
I wondered.

401
00:26:01,040 --> 00:26:02,040
No, he did not.

402
00:26:02,040 --> 00:26:07,520
He kept us right down the house with him and then a revisit to grandparents as needed.

403
00:26:07,520 --> 00:26:12,760
And he had other older ladies in the family because people jobs were for spirits.

404
00:26:12,760 --> 00:26:13,760
Cheers.

405
00:26:13,760 --> 00:26:17,200
Depression, 19, 28, 20, we're still in the depression.

406
00:26:17,200 --> 00:26:21,880
They'd come and cook and clean and my dad would pay them or whatever.

407
00:26:21,880 --> 00:26:30,920
And they were older ladies family and they'd worked out well until he married again in 1938.

408
00:26:30,920 --> 00:26:34,880
And he married then and they didn't want to have three sons of my that wife.

409
00:26:34,880 --> 00:26:41,360
And she died in 1949.

410
00:26:41,360 --> 00:26:43,520
She had three boys.

411
00:26:43,520 --> 00:26:48,520
So there we are again in the house with my dad, five boys and no mom.

412
00:26:48,520 --> 00:26:49,520
And yeah.

413
00:26:49,520 --> 00:26:50,520
Right.

414
00:26:50,520 --> 00:26:52,320
But I grew up with that wife.

415
00:26:52,320 --> 00:26:53,320
Okay.

416
00:26:53,320 --> 00:26:55,840
So she was in many ways your mother?

417
00:26:55,840 --> 00:26:56,840
Right.

418
00:26:56,840 --> 00:26:57,840
In many ways.

419
00:26:57,840 --> 00:27:01,440
One baby right after another because she was a younger woman.

420
00:27:01,440 --> 00:27:02,440
She's pretty busy.

421
00:27:02,440 --> 00:27:03,440
She's busy.

422
00:27:03,440 --> 00:27:04,440
Yeah, but that's okay.

423
00:27:04,440 --> 00:27:08,520
We are a lady in the house and it worked out fine.

424
00:27:08,520 --> 00:27:10,640
Happy to have a lady in the house.

425
00:27:10,640 --> 00:27:15,680
But then again, we as boys, five boys ended up then with older ladies coming in, cooking

426
00:27:15,680 --> 00:27:16,680
and cleaning.

427
00:27:16,680 --> 00:27:21,920
So we were raised a lot without a mother.

428
00:27:21,920 --> 00:27:26,600
And our dad met the need for both.

429
00:27:26,600 --> 00:27:27,600
So he was a busy man.

430
00:27:27,600 --> 00:27:30,720
We were always a part of his life.

431
00:27:30,720 --> 00:27:36,360
Part of his life in working, part of his life in social activities, part of his life in

432
00:27:36,360 --> 00:27:37,360
play.

433
00:27:37,360 --> 00:27:40,800
He never had to take out time for us.

434
00:27:40,800 --> 00:27:42,640
It was just everything you did.

435
00:27:42,640 --> 00:27:44,640
Everything full together.

436
00:27:44,640 --> 00:27:48,960
You know, we'd work all day and go to the river out properly run adjacent to the river

437
00:27:48,960 --> 00:27:50,360
and go and swim in.

438
00:27:50,360 --> 00:27:51,840
He beat us in the water.

439
00:27:51,840 --> 00:27:54,000
You know, he was just that kind of guy.

440
00:27:54,000 --> 00:27:55,000
And I'm not making this up.

441
00:27:55,000 --> 00:27:56,000
You know.

442
00:27:56,000 --> 00:28:00,320
But if you talk in a mind, brothers, our dad was a focal point of our life.

443
00:28:00,320 --> 00:28:01,320
Yeah.

444
00:28:01,320 --> 00:28:05,840
That doesn't mean that we didn't appreciate the grandparents and the other ladies that

445
00:28:05,840 --> 00:28:07,960
came through the family.

446
00:28:07,960 --> 00:28:10,000
But he was his parents.

447
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:13,880
We didn't miss any fairs and the circuses and things like that.

448
00:28:13,880 --> 00:28:21,040
That must have been a really remarkable childhood to the combination of the work and then

449
00:28:21,040 --> 00:28:22,640
also the opportunities.

450
00:28:22,640 --> 00:28:23,640
It was.

451
00:28:23,640 --> 00:28:31,720
And then what that did by having, I'm this small person, by having a focus mostly on one

452
00:28:31,720 --> 00:28:40,920
family person like your father who was very involved in our life.

453
00:28:40,920 --> 00:28:46,640
It created an unusual unity in cooperating amongst us.

454
00:28:46,640 --> 00:28:48,760
My dad was a leader.

455
00:28:48,760 --> 00:28:50,480
He was a boss.

456
00:28:50,480 --> 00:28:55,200
But he wasn't bossy, but he was a disciplinarian.

457
00:28:55,200 --> 00:28:59,320
Consequently, we all danced by the same music, which I mean by that.

458
00:28:59,320 --> 00:29:02,360
We all followed the same group of orders.

459
00:29:02,360 --> 00:29:07,440
And there were no any confusion being what mom said, what dad said.

460
00:29:07,440 --> 00:29:09,840
Everything coming from one direction.

461
00:29:09,840 --> 00:29:13,680
And I learned this over time and raised my own kids.

462
00:29:13,680 --> 00:29:16,080
Consequently, we bonded.

463
00:29:16,080 --> 00:29:20,080
That's more, hey, I mean, the bond even exists today.

464
00:29:20,080 --> 00:29:25,960
And I lost three brothers, you know, but if you missed with one, you missed with the whole

465
00:29:25,960 --> 00:29:26,960
crowd.

466
00:29:26,960 --> 00:29:30,600
But we always got along real well.

467
00:29:30,600 --> 00:29:33,400
We didn't fight.

468
00:29:33,400 --> 00:29:34,640
We are.

469
00:29:34,640 --> 00:29:37,680
We competed, but we got along real well.

470
00:29:37,680 --> 00:29:42,040
And some extent our wives think quite understood.

471
00:29:42,040 --> 00:29:44,240
They couldn't compete with your brothers.

472
00:29:44,240 --> 00:29:45,240
That's a fact.

473
00:29:46,240 --> 00:29:48,240
But it worked out good, you know?

474
00:29:48,240 --> 00:29:49,240
Yeah.

475
00:29:49,240 --> 00:29:59,240
What was your schooling like going to a country school and the school was like only with

476
00:29:59,240 --> 00:30:01,240
half a mile from the house, we walked school.

477
00:30:01,240 --> 00:30:04,240
Did your family provide the property for the school?

478
00:30:04,240 --> 00:30:07,440
Yes, my great grandfather won carely provided the property.

479
00:30:07,440 --> 00:30:18,480
He gave the school, he gave one, two acres by the way to build a school building on.

480
00:30:18,480 --> 00:30:23,840
And that was my grandmother, Ellen Kelly's father, Warren Kelly.

481
00:30:23,840 --> 00:30:24,840
Okay.

482
00:30:24,840 --> 00:30:35,080
And he was a descendant of Green Kelly, slave master, and his African mistress Sarah.

483
00:30:35,080 --> 00:30:38,000
And he was a mixed race kid.

484
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:41,160
And that put him in land, you know, with family connections.

485
00:30:41,160 --> 00:30:47,040
And he came out of that environment, you know, won't quite a bit of property.

486
00:30:47,040 --> 00:30:53,000
And what he did, he used his property to build his first church home and the first school

487
00:30:53,000 --> 00:30:55,480
and just kind of structured the community around it.

488
00:30:55,480 --> 00:30:59,320
Now you had other families that came and started to build with that same attitude.

489
00:30:59,320 --> 00:31:01,600
So this was not a one man show.

490
00:31:01,600 --> 00:31:05,600
And he provided the land and worked with the school system.

491
00:31:05,600 --> 00:31:12,920
And the first school was open in 1879, you know, school.

492
00:31:12,920 --> 00:31:15,120
But prior then they had school in the church.

493
00:31:15,120 --> 00:31:16,920
But that's the first school building.

494
00:31:16,920 --> 00:31:20,160
Yeah, first school building, yes ma'am.

495
00:31:20,160 --> 00:31:27,640
Now the first school itself came out of the church which was built was a one law cabin.

496
00:31:27,640 --> 00:31:29,440
What, what denomination was it?

497
00:31:29,440 --> 00:31:34,400
A shady girl, or didn't a Baptist church.

498
00:31:34,400 --> 00:31:36,000
Was it built after the Civil War?

499
00:31:36,000 --> 00:31:46,720
No, no, it was built in, well, the church itself was established in 1864.

500
00:31:46,720 --> 00:31:47,720
Okay.

501
00:31:47,720 --> 00:31:49,720
That makes sense.

502
00:31:49,720 --> 00:31:55,840
The black and the Negroes and the blacks in that state and going proud of that time was

503
00:31:55,840 --> 00:31:58,720
going to a white church, you probably heard it, haven't you?

504
00:31:58,720 --> 00:32:02,840
Well, I don't know about this particular community, but I know it was common.

505
00:32:02,840 --> 00:32:04,600
Well it didn't out community.

506
00:32:04,600 --> 00:32:11,320
The whites, you know, naturally they were subjects, you know, the plantation owners.

507
00:32:11,320 --> 00:32:16,440
And they went to the local Baptist church which is about four or five miles from where

508
00:32:16,440 --> 00:32:17,680
I would church is.

509
00:32:17,680 --> 00:32:20,320
And they obtained the church there.

510
00:32:20,320 --> 00:32:22,320
And it's a providence Baptist church.

511
00:32:22,320 --> 00:32:25,240
And it's still in existence also in this problem.

512
00:32:25,240 --> 00:32:26,880
So is it a white church now?

513
00:32:26,880 --> 00:32:30,200
That's a white church here, sure, in large church.

514
00:32:30,200 --> 00:32:43,160
And then the black church members established that church, the shady girl Baptist church.

515
00:32:43,160 --> 00:32:48,040
And the shady girl came from the first church service they had was on the, on the shady

516
00:32:48,040 --> 00:32:49,040
tree.

517
00:32:49,040 --> 00:32:50,040
Okay.

518
00:32:50,040 --> 00:32:51,040
Yeah.

519
00:32:51,040 --> 00:32:53,400
And the church we had it is right in the same place, the trees are all, but the church

520
00:32:53,400 --> 00:32:54,400
is here.

521
00:32:54,400 --> 00:32:56,400
That's too bad about the trees.

522
00:32:56,400 --> 00:32:58,800
And it was a one room long cabin.

523
00:32:58,800 --> 00:33:04,240
And that one room long cabin also served as the first school.

524
00:33:04,240 --> 00:33:06,320
Where did the teachers come from?

525
00:33:06,320 --> 00:33:07,320
Local?

526
00:33:07,320 --> 00:33:08,320
Yeah.

527
00:33:08,320 --> 00:33:09,640
Uh-huh.

528
00:33:09,640 --> 00:33:12,120
And so when you were going, when I said local came out of family.

529
00:33:12,120 --> 00:33:13,120
Yeah.

530
00:33:13,120 --> 00:33:18,720
And from the beginning, from the, from when it was first founded, the first teachers were

531
00:33:18,720 --> 00:33:22,200
family members from back in the 1870s.

532
00:33:22,200 --> 00:33:23,200
Yeah.

533
00:33:23,200 --> 00:33:24,200
Right.

534
00:33:24,200 --> 00:33:27,560
And then they get their education in slavery.

535
00:33:27,560 --> 00:33:31,440
Where did they get it in the immediate aftermath?

536
00:33:31,440 --> 00:33:32,440
That's a good question.

537
00:33:32,440 --> 00:33:37,040
That's not part of their family history.

538
00:33:37,040 --> 00:33:54,160
It was, it was obvious that education in religion was the avenue.

539
00:33:55,160 --> 00:33:57,600
Out of slavery.

540
00:33:57,600 --> 00:34:00,200
Because the first thing you're going to do is build a church.

541
00:34:00,200 --> 00:34:04,800
And the second thing you're going to do as a free slave is to build a school.

542
00:34:04,800 --> 00:34:08,160
You learn something from being what enslaved.

543
00:34:08,160 --> 00:34:10,600
Because you saw that going on around you.

544
00:34:10,600 --> 00:34:13,760
So rather than go out and you know, do something differently, what you do is you repeat

545
00:34:13,760 --> 00:34:15,400
what you've already seen.

546
00:34:15,400 --> 00:34:16,400
Yeah.

547
00:34:16,400 --> 00:34:19,440
Even though you may not have been a part of the building, you were part of what, of

548
00:34:19,440 --> 00:34:20,440
the success.

549
00:34:20,440 --> 00:34:21,440
Yeah.

550
00:34:21,440 --> 00:34:22,440
You know what freedom?

551
00:34:22,440 --> 00:34:23,440
Right.

552
00:34:23,440 --> 00:34:27,240
And then when my grandfather, my great grandfather, Warren Kelly, he educated his kids.

553
00:34:27,240 --> 00:34:28,240
Yeah.

554
00:34:28,240 --> 00:34:36,440
And when my grandfather, George Daimler, Warren, to Mary Ellen, oh, where's your education?

555
00:34:36,440 --> 00:34:40,440
And he would not, he would not permit it until what?

556
00:34:40,440 --> 00:34:46,040
Until my grandfather went to Jackson State and improved his education.

557
00:34:46,040 --> 00:34:48,920
That's where my grandmother, the Ellen Kelly had gone.

558
00:34:48,920 --> 00:34:49,920
Okay.

559
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:55,880
So there was enough education at that time coming right out of slavery, okay?

560
00:34:55,880 --> 00:35:01,800
Well, let's put it was enough forethought about education that provided people who

561
00:35:01,800 --> 00:35:03,200
had enough to teach.

562
00:35:03,200 --> 00:35:06,520
Well, there were always people that found ways to learn.

563
00:35:06,520 --> 00:35:08,160
Found ways to learn, right?

564
00:35:08,160 --> 00:35:09,160
Right.

565
00:35:09,160 --> 00:35:11,520
Even when there was a law saying you couldn't.

566
00:35:11,520 --> 00:35:12,520
Right.

567
00:35:12,520 --> 00:35:15,760
So your grandfather, George Daimler, went to Jackson State for a while?

568
00:35:15,760 --> 00:35:16,760
Yes, he did.

569
00:35:16,760 --> 00:35:17,760
Okay.

570
00:35:17,760 --> 00:35:19,160
And your father went through 10th grade.

571
00:35:19,160 --> 00:35:22,440
And he went through 10th grade in a local commuter school, in the base spring school.

572
00:35:22,440 --> 00:35:24,800
That was probably the last grade they had.

573
00:35:24,800 --> 00:35:28,480
At that time it was the last grade and there's a population increase and decrease.

574
00:35:28,480 --> 00:35:32,280
They would go from 10 to 12, back to 10 to 12.

575
00:35:32,280 --> 00:35:34,120
And at the time, my dad was going to his 10th grade.

576
00:35:34,120 --> 00:35:41,960
By the time my graduate, 1948, it was 12th grade.

577
00:35:41,960 --> 00:35:47,280
So what was, so you said that you went to the school about a half mile from your home?

578
00:35:47,280 --> 00:35:48,280
Yes.

579
00:35:48,280 --> 00:35:54,400
And what was that school like?

580
00:35:54,400 --> 00:35:59,280
Being in the commuter for you knew a lot of the kids, practiced all of the kids, except

581
00:35:59,280 --> 00:36:02,440
the ones that may be in outlying areas.

582
00:36:02,440 --> 00:36:05,560
It was, it was more like a big family reunion.

583
00:36:05,560 --> 00:36:10,440
You knew everybody and there was a lot of fun.

584
00:36:10,440 --> 00:36:14,560
And you never felt out of place.

585
00:36:14,560 --> 00:36:20,440
And the teachers that we had blended right into that same environment.

586
00:36:20,440 --> 00:36:26,040
And it was, it was a good atmosphere for learning.

587
00:36:26,040 --> 00:36:31,520
Because the education I have, the basic education, what it is and what you see and what you hear

588
00:36:31,520 --> 00:36:33,520
started right there.

589
00:36:33,520 --> 00:36:39,080
And coming out of a family, many other black families too, by the way, you know, they came

590
00:36:39,080 --> 00:36:41,440
prepared to learn.

591
00:36:41,440 --> 00:36:47,640
And my dad always had a saying a lot of the older guys and I read the kids say, hey, I'm

592
00:36:47,640 --> 00:36:49,680
not sending you to school to carry a lunch.

593
00:36:49,680 --> 00:36:53,040
But we didn't have lunch room.

594
00:36:53,040 --> 00:36:57,080
Hey, I got working at the house for you to do.

595
00:36:57,080 --> 00:36:59,880
So going to school served two purposes.

596
00:36:59,880 --> 00:37:02,280
Again, the education, plus get out a lot of hard work.

597
00:37:02,280 --> 00:37:03,280
Okay.

598
00:37:03,280 --> 00:37:05,320
So then it didn't lack a lot of motivation.

599
00:37:05,320 --> 00:37:07,880
You didn't think a lot of motivating to do it.

600
00:37:07,880 --> 00:37:08,880
Okay.

601
00:37:08,880 --> 00:37:14,480
And a whole lot of the kids, their families were not able to continue their education.

602
00:37:14,480 --> 00:37:16,080
We had a lot of dropouts.

603
00:37:16,080 --> 00:37:19,640
And that was the, as I looked back, that was the sad thing.

604
00:37:19,640 --> 00:37:23,280
For my family and there was other families, you know, allowing their kids to go on through

605
00:37:23,280 --> 00:37:24,280
and graduate.

606
00:37:24,280 --> 00:37:25,800
All of us graduated from high school.

607
00:37:25,800 --> 00:37:26,800
Yeah.

608
00:37:26,800 --> 00:37:30,520
No, I know that I've had many people tell me that they had to work so they couldn't

609
00:37:30,520 --> 00:37:31,520
keep going.

610
00:37:31,520 --> 00:37:35,760
And I saw that we got, you got to the fourth grade.

611
00:37:35,760 --> 00:37:39,560
By the time you meet to the fifth, the kids big enough to go to the fields and work, you

612
00:37:39,560 --> 00:37:42,480
start losing population.

613
00:37:42,480 --> 00:37:46,880
And by the time you got to the tenth of the eleventh grade, my class only had eight people

614
00:37:46,880 --> 00:37:47,880
at it.

615
00:37:47,880 --> 00:37:48,880
Yeah.

616
00:37:48,880 --> 00:37:52,040
And we started off with a big class, you know, in the primary.

617
00:37:52,040 --> 00:37:53,040
Yeah.

618
00:37:53,040 --> 00:37:56,040
What were your favorite subjects?

619
00:37:56,040 --> 00:38:03,240
I like math.

620
00:38:03,240 --> 00:38:07,720
I like reading.

621
00:38:07,720 --> 00:38:11,200
And math and reading.

622
00:38:11,200 --> 00:38:16,760
English had difficulty with because I could never grasp the verb and the noun and the

623
00:38:16,760 --> 00:38:17,760
pronoun.

624
00:38:17,760 --> 00:38:21,200
I could do those, but when you got over to the other parts, the subjunctive.

625
00:38:21,200 --> 00:38:22,200
Yeah.

626
00:38:22,200 --> 00:38:23,200
Whatever that is.

627
00:38:23,200 --> 00:38:26,240
And I kind of tuned it out because I figured I didn't need it anyway.

628
00:38:26,240 --> 00:38:28,240
I found out later that I did.

629
00:38:28,240 --> 00:38:31,760
And so I had to go back and do some remedial study to move ahead.

630
00:38:31,760 --> 00:38:33,080
You didn't see any need for it.

631
00:38:33,080 --> 00:38:35,720
But those were my favorite and favorite subjects.

632
00:38:35,720 --> 00:38:40,680
And then later on, when I said later on, when I got to being about the fifth or sixth

633
00:38:40,680 --> 00:38:46,600
grade, we had a spelling class when the kids get up before the class and the teacher would

634
00:38:46,600 --> 00:38:48,000
call your word and you spell it.

635
00:38:48,000 --> 00:38:50,240
I fell in love with spelling.

636
00:38:50,240 --> 00:38:54,680
And the way it happened was my dad drove a school bus and when he come to pick up the kids,

637
00:38:54,680 --> 00:38:58,000
the spelling was the last class at the end of the day.

638
00:38:58,000 --> 00:39:01,240
And he'd become to my classroom.

639
00:39:01,240 --> 00:39:06,320
And here I am up at the board, writing my spelling letters that the teacher would call

640
00:39:06,320 --> 00:39:07,320
them out.

641
00:39:07,320 --> 00:39:11,320
And my dad's watching me misspeel these words.

642
00:39:11,320 --> 00:39:12,320
Okay.

643
00:39:12,320 --> 00:39:17,040
So when we get home at night, he says, get the spelling book.

644
00:39:17,040 --> 00:39:21,200
And we sit down in front of the fireplace, Kerosene lamp.

645
00:39:21,200 --> 00:39:23,000
And he called me those words.

646
00:39:23,000 --> 00:39:25,680
And if I miss one, he bumped me upside the head.

647
00:39:25,680 --> 00:39:29,160
And after a while, you know, I got where I learned, and then I learned how to what.

648
00:39:29,160 --> 00:39:31,440
Identify syllables.

649
00:39:31,440 --> 00:39:32,920
And then I do pretty well at that.

650
00:39:32,920 --> 00:39:36,360
And so that turned out to be helped a lot.

651
00:39:36,360 --> 00:39:39,520
Was it, did you enjoy doing that with your dad or was it pressure?

652
00:39:39,520 --> 00:39:40,520
No, I didn't enjoy it.

653
00:39:40,520 --> 00:39:41,520
No, I didn't enjoy it.

654
00:39:41,520 --> 00:39:42,520
No, I didn't enjoy it.

655
00:39:42,520 --> 00:39:46,000
I didn't bump up so I did, you know.

656
00:39:46,000 --> 00:39:49,120
You have to learn how to act under pressure if you're going to do it.

657
00:39:49,120 --> 00:39:50,120
That's exactly right.

658
00:39:50,120 --> 00:39:56,360
So, but all in all the school turned out well, graduated, you know, on time, 18 years

659
00:39:56,360 --> 00:39:57,360
old.

660
00:39:57,680 --> 00:39:59,200
I've talked to a few people.

661
00:39:59,200 --> 00:40:02,400
I think they're a little younger than you and they went to different schools.

662
00:40:02,400 --> 00:40:08,720
But one person was telling me that she had a, she didn't call it civics class.

663
00:40:08,720 --> 00:40:11,760
I can't remember what she called it, but she said that the teacher actually talked to

664
00:40:11,760 --> 00:40:14,280
them about voting in their class.

665
00:40:14,280 --> 00:40:18,640
Did you ever have any kind of, yes, yes, I don't want to miss that piece.

666
00:40:18,640 --> 00:40:25,440
Our principal was progressive.

667
00:40:25,520 --> 00:40:30,320
He was educated.

668
00:40:30,320 --> 00:40:39,400
He saw, he saw the need for education and, that was my thought.

669
00:40:39,400 --> 00:40:41,400
I asked you about voting teachers.

670
00:40:41,400 --> 00:40:42,640
Oh, yeah, yeah.

671
00:40:42,640 --> 00:40:49,360
He saw the need for the education and he was really in tune with African American history,

672
00:40:49,360 --> 00:40:50,360
Negro history.

673
00:40:50,360 --> 00:40:53,840
I learned about Book of T. Washington, you know, early in the stage.

674
00:40:53,840 --> 00:40:59,160
George Washington, Carver, the Underground Railroad.

675
00:40:59,160 --> 00:41:03,840
And all of those things I learned right there in the 1940s.

676
00:41:03,840 --> 00:41:10,400
We had a little thin, green, black history book and I went looking for one when I returned

677
00:41:10,400 --> 00:41:17,840
home and it identified the prominent Negroes back in that day.

678
00:41:17,840 --> 00:41:23,800
Then that it really made a difference in bringing us forward as far as education is concerned.

679
00:41:23,800 --> 00:41:30,800
And I tried to find it and he acquired that book and then we had to, it was a part of

680
00:41:30,800 --> 00:41:31,800
the curriculum.

681
00:41:31,800 --> 00:41:34,920
It's seventh and eighth grade.

682
00:41:34,920 --> 00:41:40,840
So I had a real good feel of what blacks had done up that period.

683
00:41:40,840 --> 00:41:46,800
You're invented to cotton gin and things that came along in the era, okay?

684
00:41:46,800 --> 00:41:49,200
Did you have any sense of the politics behind that?

685
00:41:49,200 --> 00:41:50,200
No.

686
00:41:50,200 --> 00:41:52,880
Because, of course, the white school district, you know, the white school district, you

687
00:41:52,880 --> 00:41:59,080
know, the white, you know, I imagine that your school had a black principal and then probably

688
00:41:59,080 --> 00:42:00,080
a white superintendent or something.

689
00:42:00,080 --> 00:42:01,080
White superintendent.

690
00:42:01,080 --> 00:42:05,840
And the most of our textbooks came from the white schools because they passed, they used

691
00:42:05,840 --> 00:42:08,880
textbooks down to the black schools.

692
00:42:08,880 --> 00:42:09,880
Right.

693
00:42:09,880 --> 00:42:11,200
Some of them have pages missing.

694
00:42:11,200 --> 00:42:14,640
You see names of other kids, you know, but they were books.

695
00:42:14,640 --> 00:42:18,120
Did you think about that at the time that you're getting these second handbooks or anything?

696
00:42:18,120 --> 00:42:19,120
No, I didn't.

697
00:42:19,120 --> 00:42:22,840
Did you have any sense of the white kids school or did you have any contact with them?

698
00:42:22,840 --> 00:42:23,840
No, I didn't.

699
00:42:23,840 --> 00:42:28,600
The white school was only about two and a half, three miles away and they lived in another

700
00:42:28,600 --> 00:42:29,600
world.

701
00:42:29,600 --> 00:42:32,800
But now, their property that joined ours, we would see them.

702
00:42:32,800 --> 00:42:34,320
We knew them.

703
00:42:34,320 --> 00:42:35,560
But we went to separate schools.

704
00:42:35,560 --> 00:42:37,080
Everything was separate.

705
00:42:37,080 --> 00:42:41,360
Separate churches schools, you know, separate theaters when you went to town and we went

706
00:42:41,360 --> 00:42:43,880
to have a chance to go to the movie.

707
00:42:43,880 --> 00:42:46,680
You know, we didn't have any social interaction.

708
00:42:46,680 --> 00:42:53,960
Or maybe we didn't have a creek swimming, you know, on a hot summer day and played just

709
00:42:53,960 --> 00:42:55,280
like nothing ever happened.

710
00:42:55,280 --> 00:42:57,040
I grew up with them.

711
00:42:57,040 --> 00:43:00,360
But we didn't, socially we didn't, we didn't mix outside of that.

712
00:43:00,360 --> 00:43:03,680
I know you said that your dad's store had white customers.

713
00:43:03,680 --> 00:43:04,680
And white customers?

714
00:43:04,680 --> 00:43:07,520
Did he ever have white people working on the land?

715
00:43:07,520 --> 00:43:08,520
Yes.

716
00:43:08,520 --> 00:43:13,760
There were some poor in the community that were just so poor that they would come and

717
00:43:13,760 --> 00:43:15,680
they'd work in the cotton fields.

718
00:43:15,680 --> 00:43:17,560
Pick cotton.

719
00:43:17,560 --> 00:43:23,840
And I do remember they wouldn't be in mixed up.

720
00:43:23,840 --> 00:43:27,800
They'd like maybe a part of the field but not the distance away.

721
00:43:27,800 --> 00:43:33,080
Little segment here, blacks and little segment there, all a journey, picking cotton together.

722
00:43:33,080 --> 00:43:34,080
Yeah.

723
00:43:34,080 --> 00:43:35,080
Right.

724
00:43:35,080 --> 00:43:40,560
But now they were extremely poor white folks to do that.

725
00:43:40,560 --> 00:43:43,920
They really, that they would have to have a pretty desperate need and order.

726
00:43:43,920 --> 00:43:44,920
Very desperate need.

727
00:43:44,920 --> 00:43:47,080
Very desperate need, yes.

728
00:43:47,080 --> 00:43:48,080
Yeah.

729
00:43:48,080 --> 00:43:52,240
But we didn't look at them as being poor just some white folks, you know, come pick cotton.

730
00:43:52,240 --> 00:43:53,240
Yeah.

731
00:43:53,240 --> 00:43:54,240
Yeah.

732
00:43:54,240 --> 00:43:58,800
I mean, when you were working in the store or when your dad had the store, were there

733
00:43:58,800 --> 00:44:02,160
ever any issues with white customers or did things go pretty good?

734
00:44:02,160 --> 00:44:09,080
My dad had had not malicious, you know, not our organ and that.

735
00:44:09,080 --> 00:44:12,200
And white customers coming take his goods and we didn't pay him because my dad could

736
00:44:12,200 --> 00:44:13,880
not make them pay.

